Power Plants in the World

Update date: January, 2022

  • Data source

World Power Plant Data Visualized

From the Global Database of Power Plants created by WRI and their partners, I will analyze the energy production capacity and primary fuel information between different countries and individual plants.

I want to compare the sizes of different power plants. There is information about the plant capacity, as well as the actual and estimated energy production (estimation method is described in the documentation of the database). However, very few power plants have actually publically disclosed the generation data, so I will use the capacity data for now. The amount of the NaN values in different columns confirms this.

Indeed, all power plants have capacity information but only about 25% include data about actual electricity generation. The estimation model, on the other hand, has been applied to 95% of the plants.

I'll compare the plants based on their primary fuel, as well as the capacity data. First questions:

  • How many power plants use each primary fuel?
  • What is the total capacity (MW) of all primary fuels globally?
In [3]:

Some remarks from the results:

  • Solar, hydro and wind power are the most used forms of energy measured in the number of plants
  • However, solar and wind energy are only the 7th and 5th largest energy forms in combined energy capacity
  • The most efficient fuels (comparing the average power plant capacity) seem to be nuclear, coal and gas

Moving on, I'm adding another grouper, based on whether the primary fuel is renewable or not. I'll use it to calculate which countries can produce the most renewable energy compared to non-renewable energy.

In [5]:
data['renewable'] = np.where(data['primary_fuel'].isin(['Geothermal', 'Hydro', 'Solar', 'Wave and Tidal', 'Wind', 'Biomass', 'Waste']), 1, 0)
In [6]:

In [7]:
renew = renew.pivot(index='country_long', columns='renewable', values='total_capacity')
renew = renew.reset_index().rename_axis(None,axis='columns')
renew = renew.rename(columns={1.0:'renewable_mw', 0.0:'nonrenewable_mw'})
renew = renew.replace(np.NaN, 0)
renew['renewable_ratio'] = renew.renewable_mw / (renew.renewable_mw + renew.nonrenewable_mw)
renew.sort_values('renewable_ratio', ascending=False)

I'll calculate the activity of each plant, based on the estimated energy generation (2017) and the capacity data. Dividing these with each other tells how many hours the plant would've had to run at maximum capacity, in order to meet the estimate. I'm also making the same calculation for the published energy generation in 2017.

In [17]:
estimated_runtime_Nordic = powerplantsNordic.iloc[:,[1,2,4,7,17,22,30]]

estimated_runtime_Nordic.loc[:,'estimated_running_hours_2017'] = estimated_runtime_Nordic.loc[:,'estimated_generation_gwh_2017'] * 1000 / estimated_runtime_Nordic.loc[:,'capacity_mw']
estimated_runtime_Nordic.loc[:,'running_hours_2017'] = estimated_runtime_Nordic.loc[:,'generation_gwh_2017'] * 1000 / estimated_runtime_Nordic.loc[:,'capacity_mw']
estimated_runtime_Nordic = estimated_runtime_Nordic.sort_values(by='estimated_running_hours_2017', ascending=False)

Calculated values seem consistent. I'll find out if capacity correlates with the running hours at all (so that larger plants would be kept running much more or much less than smaller ones). I'll create a scatter plot of individual values of these.

In [21]:
estimated_runtime_Nordic.corrwith(estimated_runtime_Nordic['estimated_running_hours_2017'])['capacity_mw']
Out[21]:
0.07031979451162944

Analysis results:

  • Correlation between running hours and capacity seems to be nonexistent across all fuel types (confirmed by the correlation calculation above)
  • In most cases, running hours seem to correlate with the fuel type (in the chart the points of same color often fall on the same horizontal line). However, we have to remember that the data used for this plot is generated by a machine learning model, which might compensate the missing energy generation data by assuming the aforementioned correlation. I wouldn't draw strong conclusions based on this observation.

For comparison, I will draw the same plot using the actual published generation data.

In [22]:

The points seem to lie more scattered but the lack of data makes it difficult to see the trend well. Also, there are definitely inconsistencies with the data since the calculated runtimes in some cases exceed the number of hours in a year (8760).
